## The Numbers Don't Lie

April 2026 was an active month in the world of food recalls. According to the latest data, the year-to-date total for recalls stands at a worrying **317**, of which **87 were Class I recalls**, indicating significant health risks. This means we are on track to surpass previous years' recall counts, an achievement no one should celebrate.

## Offenders in the Spotlight

This month, some of the usual suspects made their appearance yet again. **Moonlight Packing Corporation** and **Albertsons Companies LLC** continue to top the charts for the brands with the worst recall track records, each racking up double-digit Class I recalls. But they're not alone--new entries like **Diva Fam Inc.** and **Pure Vitamins and Natural Supplements, LLC** are making their mark as well, albeit for all the wrong reasons. The latter, for instance, was caught selling products adulterated with undeclared pharmaceutical ingredients; a big no-no by any measure.

## The Main Culprits

As we analyze the reasons behind the recalls, it's clear that allergens and labeling issues remain endemic: 
- **178 recalls were due to allergens**, a figure representing over half of the year's recalls. Mislabeling and undeclared allergens are not just an inconvenience; they are lifethreatening hazards for those affected.
- **Mislabeling products** (4 recalls so far this year) causes confusion and poses risks to unsuspecting consumers. For example, products that misstate their ingredients or present false nutritional information.

## Focusing on the Consequences

Such recalls have real-life impacts. The recent mislabeling of allergen-containing products by Booey's Gourmet LLC's Dragon's Breath sauce is emblematic of the problem. While the sauce label listed anchovy and sesame, it failed to highlight these as allergens in a 'contains' statement, exposing allergic individuals to unnecessary risks.
